Generative Adversarial Network (GAN) with CIFAR10

by Denis Osipychev < www.denisos.com >

In this demo, I am building a generative adversarial network (GAN) trained on the CIFAR dataset and capable of creating synthetic images following the CIFAR data distribution.

This is an extension of the previous demonstration building a GAN for MNIST dataset. You can find general remarks about GANs there.

General packages import¶

Create a Discriminator¶

This time, the discriminator follows the architecture of a simple CNN-based classifier for CIFAR10 dataset. It has 3 conv layers followed by 1 dense layer. The only difference is a sigmoid activation function applied to the output.

In [4]:
class Discriminator(nn.Module):

    def __init__(self):
        super(Discriminator, self).__init__()
        
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(3, 64, 3, stride=1, padding=1)
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(64, 128, 3, stride=1, padding=1)
        self.conv3 = nn.Conv2d(128, 256, 3, stride=1, padding=1)
        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(0.5)
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(4096, 128)
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(128, 1)
        
    def forward(self, x):
        norm_noise = 0.1 * torch.randn(x.size(), device=device) # adding noise to input to avoid D overfitting
        x = x + norm_noise
        x = F.leaky_relu(self.conv1(x), 0.2)
        x = F.max_pool2d(x,2)
        x = F.leaky_relu(self.conv2(x), 0.2)
        x = F.max_pool2d(x,2)
        x = F.leaky_relu(self.conv3(x), 0.2)
        x = F.max_pool2d(x,2)
        x = x.view(-1, 4096)
        x = F.leaky_relu(self.fc1(x), 0.2)
        x = self.dropout(x)
        x = torch.sigmoid(self.fc2(x))
        
        return x

img_shape = images[0].shape    
D = Discriminator().to(device)
print(D)

Discriminator(
  (conv1): Conv2d(3, 64, kernel_size=(3, 3), stride=(1, 1), padding=(1, 1))
  (conv2): Conv2d(64, 128, kernel_size=(3, 3), stride=(1, 1), padding=(1, 1))
  (conv3): Conv2d(128, 256, kernel_size=(3, 3), stride=(1, 1), padding=(1, 1))
  (dropout): Dropout(p=0.5, inplace=False)
  (fc1): Linear(in_features=4096, out_features=128, bias=True)
  (fc2): Linear(in_features=128, out_features=1, bias=True)
)

Create a Generator¶

Similar to the previous demo, the generator is pretty much a flipped discriminator. It has 3 layers of deconvolution with strides to upsample the features followed by a single convolutional layer to wrap up the image to a cirtain shape. $Tanh$ activation is applied at the end similar to the MNIST GAN.

In [5]:
class Generator(nn.Module):

    def __init__(self, input_size):
        super(Generator, self).__init__()
        
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(input_size, 4096)
        self.convt1 = nn.ConvTranspose2d(256, 128, 3, stride=2, padding=0, output_padding=0)
        self.convt2 = nn.ConvTranspose2d(128, 64, 3, stride=2, padding=1, output_padding=0)
        self.convt3 = nn.ConvTranspose2d(64, 64, 3, stride=2, padding=2, output_padding=1)
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(64, 3, 3, stride=1, padding=1)

    def forward(self, x):
        x = F.leaky_relu(self.fc1(x), 0.2) # (input, negative_slope=0.2)
        x = x.view(-1,256,4,4)
        x = F.leaky_relu(self.convt1(x), 0.2)
        x = F.leaky_relu(self.convt2(x), 0.2)
        x = F.leaky_relu(self.convt3(x), 0.2)
        x = torch.tanh(self.conv1(x))
        return x

z_size = 100
G = Generator(z_size).to(device)
print(G)

Generator(
  (fc1): Linear(in_features=100, out_features=4096, bias=True)
  (convt1): ConvTranspose2d(256, 128, kernel_size=(3, 3), stride=(2, 2))
  (convt2): ConvTranspose2d(128, 64, kernel_size=(3, 3), stride=(2, 2), padding=(1, 1))
  (convt3): ConvTranspose2d(64, 64, kernel_size=(3, 3), stride=(2, 2), padding=(2, 2), output_padding=(1, 1))
  (conv1): Conv2d(64, 3, kernel_size=(3, 3), stride=(1, 1), padding=(1, 1))
)

Create Optimizers¶

In GANs, the generator and discriminator variables are updated separately. So, we'll compute two separete sets of losses and utilize two independent Adam optimizers.

In [6]:
lr = 0.0002

# Create optimizers for the discriminator and generator
d_optimizer = optim.Adam(D.parameters(), lr)
g_optimizer = optim.Adam(G.parameters(), lr)

loss = nn.BCELoss().to(device)

GAN Training¶

Training will alternate between training the discriminator and the generator.

Discriminator training¶

  1. Compute the discriminator loss on real, training images
  2. Compute the discriminator loss on fake, generated images
  3. Add up real and fake loss
  4. Perform an optimization step

Generator training¶

  1. Compute the discriminator loss on fake images, using target labels
  2. Perform an optimization step

Important thing to note¶

The discriminator learns to identify the output of the generator. After certain point, it will overfit to the generator and their losses start to diverge. To mitigate this undesired behavior, we apply the following tricks:

  1. One-sided label smoothing - avoid discriminator being overconfigent about the prediction
  2. Adding normal noise to real images - reduce discriminator performance

More tricks can be found here: https://machinelearningmastery.com/how-to-train-stable-generative-adversarial-networks/

In [7]:
num_epochs = 100
writer = SummaryWriter('./log/gan') #Tensorboard

samples = []
losses = []

# make a fixed vector in latent space to track the evolution of the generator
z_sample = torch.randn(10, z_size, device=device)

# train the network
D.train()
G.train()

update_step = 0
for epoch in range(num_epochs):
    for real_images, _ in train_loader:
            
        batch_size = real_images.size(0)
        real_images = real_images.to(device)
        
        # ============================================
        #            TRAIN THE DISCRIMINATOR
        # ============================================
        
        d_optimizer.zero_grad()
        
        # Compute loss with real images
        D_real = D(real_images)
        
        target_labels = 0.9 * torch.ones(batch_size, device=device) # so called label smoothing to avoid D overfitting
        d_real_loss = loss(D_real.squeeze(), target_labels)
        
        # Compute loss with fake images        
        z = torch.randn(batch_size, z_size, device=device)
        fake_images = G(z)
        fake_images = fake_images.detach()
        D_fake = D(fake_images)
        
        target_labels = torch.zeros(batch_size, device=device)
        d_fake_loss = loss(D_fake.squeeze(), target_labels)
        
        # add up loss and perform backprop step
        d_loss = d_real_loss + d_fake_loss
        d_loss.backward()
        d_optimizer.step()
        
        # =========================================
        #            TRAIN THE GENERATOR
        # =========================================
        
        g_optimizer.zero_grad()
        
        # Compute generator loss with fake image
        z = torch.randn(2*batch_size, z_size, device=device)
        fake_images = G(z)
        D_fake = D(fake_images)
        
        target_labels = torch.ones(2*batch_size, device=device)
        g_loss = loss(D_fake.squeeze(), target_labels)
        
        # perform backprop step
        g_loss.backward()
        g_optimizer.step()

        # Print stats
        update_step += 1
        if update_step%100 == 0:
            dl_mean, gl_mean = torch.mean(d_loss), torch.mean(g_loss)
            writer.add_scalar('Loss/Generator', gl_mean, update_step) #Tensorboard
            writer.add_scalar('Loss/Discriminator', dl_mean, update_step) #Tensorboard
            print('\r Epoch [%d/%d] | d_loss: %f | g_loss: %f'%(epoch+1, num_epochs, dl_mean, gl_mean), end="")
    
    
    ## Save progress after each epoch
    losses.append((torch.mean(d_loss), torch.mean(g_loss)))
    
    G.eval()
    sample = G(z_sample)
    samples.append(sample.to('cpu'))
    G.train()

# Save training samples and the generator model
writer.close() #Tensorboard
torch.save(G, './cifar_gan.pkl')
with open('./cifar_gan_samples.pkl', 'wb') as f:
    pkl.dump(samples, f)

Show the Evolution of the Generator¶

The generator starts with generating a random noize. After each batch update, the generated images look more similar to those in the real dataset.

In [9]:
# with open('./cifar_gan_samples.pkl', 'rb') as f:
#     samples = pkl.load(f)
    
n_rows = 10
n_cols = 10

fig, axes = plt.subplots(figsize=(20,20), nrows=n_rows, ncols=n_cols, sharex=True, sharey=True)
for i_row in range(n_rows):
    for i_col in range(n_cols):
        b = int(len(samples)/n_rows) * i_row
        img = samples[b][i_col]
        img = img.detach()
        img = img.numpy().transpose((1,2,0))/2 + 0.5
        ax = axes[i_row, i_col]
        ax.imshow(img)
        ax.xaxis.set_visible(False)
        ax.yaxis.set_visible(False)

Sampling the Generator¶

We can also get completely new images from the generator by sampling input vectors in the latent space.

In [10]:
# load generator model
# G = torch.load('./cifar_gan.pkl')

# generate random vectors in latent space and pipe them to the generator
sample_size=100
z = torch.randn(sample_size, z_size, device=device)
E = G.eval()
images = G(z)
images = images.detach().to('cpu')

fig, axes = plt.subplots(figsize=(20,20), nrows=10, ncols=10, sharex=True, sharey=True)
for i in range(sample_size):
    img = images[i]
    img = img.numpy().transpose((1,2,0))/2 + 0.5
    ax = axes[i//10, i%10]
    ax.imshow(img)
    ax.xaxis.set_visible(False)
    ax.yaxis.set_visible(False)
